item.description:
Helpful context:
Turing Machines - The Minimal Model of Everything a Computer Can Do In 1936, Turing proved something devastating: no program can exist that takes any program $P$ and any input $X$ as arguments and correctly answers &ldquo;will $P(X)$ halt, or run forever?&rdquo;
This is not a limitation of current hardware. It is not a gap in our current mathematics. It is not a problem that a sufficiently advanced civilization could solve.

Helpful context:
Law of Large Numbers &amp; CLT - Why Averages Behave The Central Limit Theorem tells you something beautiful: the sample mean converges to the true mean, and the fluctuations around it are approximately Normal. But there&rsquo;s a catch hidden in the word &ldquo;approximately.&rdquo;
The CLT is an asymptotic result. It holds &ldquo;in the limit as $n \to \infty$.&rdquo; For any specific sample size - say $n = 100$ or $n = 10000$ - the CLT gives you no concrete guarantee.

Helpful context:
Word Embeddings - Meaning as Position in Space Gradient Descent - Follow the Slope Until the Ground Levels Off &ldquo;The animal didn&rsquo;t cross the street because it was too tired.&rdquo;
What does &ldquo;it&rdquo; refer to? The animal. Not the street. Your brain figured this out in milliseconds by holding the subject of the clause in memory while processing the rest of the sentence. This is effortless for you, but it is something a standard feedforward neural network genuinely cannot do.

Helpful context:
Recurrent Neural Networks - Memory Hidden in the Hidden State Probability as a Language - The Grammar of Uncertainty Entropy &amp; Information Theory - The Mathematics of Surprise &ldquo;The cat sat on the ___.&rdquo;
Your brain fills in &ldquo;mat&rdquo; (or &ldquo;floor&rdquo; or &ldquo;sofa&rdquo;) without thinking. You don&rsquo;t consciously enumerate possibilities and weigh them - the prediction just happens. What you&rsquo;re doing, without realizing it, is running a language model.

Helpful context:
Sequence Modeling &amp; Language Models - Predicting One Token at a Time Linear Transformations - Geometry Encoded as Arithmetic Read this sentence: &ldquo;The trophy doesn&rsquo;t fit in the suitcase because it is too big.&rdquo;
You immediately know that &ldquo;it&rdquo; refers to the trophy - the trophy is what&rsquo;s too big to fit. You didn&rsquo;t run through every possible referent and weigh them consciously. Your eye slid back to &ldquo;trophy&rdquo; and the meaning snapped into place.

The most unfrequented quarter of the town, they always told,
Quite a prison it was, for a mischievous six year old;
That was the day we moved in, cloud envelopes had brought a chill,
But it wasn&rsquo;t long before I found the next-door girl staring aghast from behind the grille.
She looked much elder but it was hard to keep her queer, eccentric disposition covered,
The benign look, those bewildered eyes spoke long tales of agony, of being abhorred;

Behold! The majestic vapours on their rise, bubbling out from the purple hue;
The cauldron of yearnings was brewing its likely propitious road;
Never had I seen such spectacle of starry dreams of glitter blue;
So many dipped in its soothing, rewarding broth to revel in its free abode.
Allured, I headed towards this nirvana but alas! fate had forbidden it for me;
I fought and bellowed but only to settle to rest, plunging into desolation;

I found myself in a clear glass pitcher;
Looking through its walls with famished eyes;
To think, peruse, justify and be abler;
I did imbibe in the preachings of the learned wise.
I learnt to explore the near and yonder;
As the time wheel cycled its way unheeded;
I jumped, slid till the glass got scratches of ponder;
I thought all was forever unfolded.
But then I heard weary footsteps draw closer to me;

He was intolerant, stubborn and stagnant;
Until he realised his views were all vacant.
He was a believer of blind prejudice;
Until he realised that it is all sheer injustice.
He used to discriminate against and abuse others,
Until he realised that he has no one to stand for him as a brother.
He used to hate the impoverished and ugly;
Until he realised it was him who was poor, repulsive and guilty.
